04537nam a22005895i 9780822392224DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223922247 a10.1515/97808223922242doi  a(DE-B1597)553699  a(OCoLC)404069727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM851b.H546 2009 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a303.48/331 aHillis, Ken, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOnline a Lot of the Time :bRitual, Fetish, Sign /cKen Hillis. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b11 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- t>>> Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Rituals of Transmission, Fetishizing the Trace -- t1 Rituals -- t2 Fetishes -- t3 Signs -- t4 "Avatars Become /me" Depiction Dethrones Description -- t5 So Near, So Far, and Both at Once Telefetishism and Rituals of Visibility -- tAfterword Digital Affectivity -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA wedding ceremony in a Web-based virtual world. Online memorials commemorating the dead. A coffee klatch attended by persons thousands of miles apart via webcams. These are just a few of the ritual practices that have developed and are emerging in online settings. Such Web-based rituals depend on the merging of two modes of communication often held distinct by scholars: the use of a device or mechanism to transmit messages between people across space, and a ritual gathering of people in the same place for the performance of activities intended to generate, maintain, repair, and renew social relations. In Online a Lot of the Time, Ken Hillis explores the stakes when rituals that would formerly have required participants to gather in one physical space are reformulated for the Web. In so doing, he develops a theory of how ritual, fetish, and signification translate to online environments and offer new forms of visual and spatial interaction. The online environments Hillis examines reflect the dynamic contradictions at the core of identity and the ways these contradictions get signified.Hillis analyzes forms of ritual and fetishism made possible through second-generation virtual environments such as Second Life and the popular practice of using webcams to "lifecast" one's life online twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week. Discussing how people create and identify with their electronic avatars, he shows how the customs of virtual-world chat reinforce modern consumer-based subjectivities, allowing individuals to both identify with and distance themselves from their characters. His consideration of web-cam cultures links the ritual of exposing one's life online to a politics of visibility. Hillis argues that these new "rituals of transmission" are compelling because they provide a seemingly material trace of the actual person on the other side of the interface.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aInternet gamesxSocial aspects. 0aOnline identities. 0aOnline social networks. 0aShared virtual environmentsxSocial aspects. 0aWeb 2.0xSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392224zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392224.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles